comments.body:
@SergeyBear that won't work.

You need to use unshare before using any other buildah command.

@TomasTomecek already solved the issue he was having that way.  I think we can close this issue

@SergeyBear the problem is that what we want to achieve is not permitted.  Once the process exits, there is no mount point that will survive it, and this is done for good reasons as an unprivileged user cannot mount stuff on the host.

We need to stay in the same namespace, where the mount exists and is accessible.

I am not trying to avoid fixing it, it is just not possible :-)

@rhatdan

In addition to the case mentioned above, similarly: what would it take to mount the container to a path on the host, then use Python to perform file operations to alter the container, using something like [Plumbum](https://plumbum.readthedocs.io/)?

Is there another way to mount the container filesystem that allows more access from external programs?

@AndydeCleyre Would you be interesting in writing up a short blog?  It might be of more interest if you wrote it using  podman rather then buildah.  I think podman has more users, but it would be exactly the same.
```
#!/usr/bin/env -S podman unshare -- python3
```
